This thread is practically a rehash of numerous existing threads:<br /><br /><a href="http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=7002" class="postlink">http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=7002</a><br /><a href="http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=6588" class="postlink">http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=6588</a><br /><a href="http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=4955" class="postlink">http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=4955</a><br /><a href="http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=4822" class="postlink">http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=4822</a><br /><br />Sorry to sound like The Grinch, but:<br /><br />Become more familiar with the tools you use.  Questions like "why doesn't the tool do what I'm hoping it will do?" (effectively that is the question being asked in the OP) are, and I do mean this sincerely, completely silly.<br /><br />I'm not sure what it's going to take for people to actually sit down and read the documentation that's associated with the tools they use.  If the tool doesn't come with any documentation, don't use it -- yes really.  I wouldn't trust any low-level tool (that includes assemblers) which doesn't come with documentation outlining syntax, macros, and other functionalities.<br /><br />There's a reason I recommend asm6 to people these days, and it's because the syntax matches what those of us "old timers" are used to, meaning it's what you'll find used in most books, 6502 tutorials, and so on.  But ultimately every assembler is different.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3">koitsu</a> — Thu Dec 09, 2010 4:27 pm</p><hr />
