<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[tepples]]></name></author>
<updated>2010-12-09T05:45:19-07:00</updated>
<published>2010-12-09T05:45:19-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7251&amp;p=71249#p71249</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7251&amp;p=71249#p71249"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[NESASM3 Doesn't Use Zero-Page?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7251&amp;p=71249#p71249"><![CDATA[
The standard for 6502 family is as follows<br /><ul><li>Brackets are used for indirection with a 3-byte pointer, which is valid only on 65C816. </li><li>The outermost parentheses are used for indirection with a 2-byte pointer. </li><li>Inner parentheses are used to set precedence in numeric expressions. </li></ul>As I understand it, NESASM uses a different naming convention:<br /><ul><li>Brackets are used for indirection with a 2-byte pointer. </li><li>Parentheses are used only to set precedence in numeric expressions. </li></ul><br />As for $B2, it's not entirely silliness. NESASM was based on an assembler for TG16, which has a 65C02 family CPU. This also shows up in NESASM's preference for the 8 KiB bank size of MMC3-class mappers, which matches that of the TG16.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Thu Dec 09, 2010 5:45 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
